<Layout
  title="Hot Water Narre Warren | Gas, Heat-Pump, Solar, Same-Day Repairs | (03) 9003 0108"
  description="Hot water specialists in Narre Warren — same-day repairs, gas / heat-pump / solar / electric replacements. Narre Warren, Narre Warren North, Narre Warren South, Fountain Gate. Solar Vic rebate. VBA-licensed."
  canonical="https://sehotwater.com.au/narre-warren/">
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Narre Warren &middot; Narre Warren North / South &middot; Fountain Gate</span>
      <h1>Hot water in <span class="accent">Narre Warren</span>.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        Narre Warren is mortgage-belt 3&ndash;4 bedroom family country &mdash;
        high hot water demand, gas instantaneous on the side wall, units now
        12&ndash;18 years old and starting to fail. Same-day repairs anywhere
        in 3805, heat-pump conversions with the $1,000 Solar Vic rebate
        handled in-house.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Book a free quote</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Why Narre Warren</span>
      <h2>The Narre Warren hot water story.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <h3>The 2005&ndash;2012 Rinnai Infinity bulge.</h3>
        <p>
          Most of Narre Warren and Narre Warren South was built or
          re-developed between 2005 and 2012. Default install at the time was
          a Rinnai Infinity 24 or 26 gas instantaneous mounted externally on
          the side or rear wall, ducted off internal copper. Those units are
          now 13&ndash;20 years old &mdash; a Rinnai Infinity easily lasts 20+
          years but the electronic ignition board is the wear-out point.
          Symptoms: unit clicks but doesn&rsquo;t fire, intermittent hot, error
          codes 11 / 12 / 14 on the controller. Board replacement is
          $400&ndash;$650; full unit replacement starts to make sense at the
          20-year mark.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">3-4 bedroom family homes &mdash; size matters.</h3>
        <p>
          Narre Warren is family country. 3&ndash;4 bedroom homes, 2 bathrooms,
          dishwasher, washing machine, kids in showers morning and evening.
          A 20L/min Infinity 24 was undersized from day one for many of these
          households &mdash; the lukewarm-shower-when-dishwasher-runs problem.
          We upsize to 26L/min Infinity or Bosch Highflow 26e on most
          replacements. For families ready to electrify, a 280&ndash;315L
          heat-pump comfortably handles peak demand.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Heat-pump conversion is the smart upgrade.</h3>
        <p>
          For an owner-occupier family in Narre Warren paying ~$1,000/year for
          gas hot water, a heat-pump conversion (Reclaim 280L, Sanden 315L,
          Stiebel Eltron 300L) lands at $3K&ndash;$4.5K net after the $1,000
          Solar Vic rebate plus STCs. Running cost drops to ~$300/year &mdash;
          $700/year saving, 4&ndash;5 year payback on the conversion premium.
          We mount compressors on the side wall well clear of bedroom windows;
          most installs are sound-rated 45&ndash;48 dB and inaudible inside.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Typical Narre Warren jobs.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Rinnai Infinity 24 board replacement (15-year-old unit) &mdash; $400&ndash;$650</li>
          <li>Infinity 24 to Infinity 26 upgrade (sized for family demand) &mdash; $2.3K&ndash;$2.8K</li>
          <li>Gas instantaneous to heat-pump conversion (Reclaim 280L) &mdash; $3.5K&ndash;$4.5K net after rebates</li>
          <li>Heat-pump compressor placement next to existing AC condenser</li>
          <li>Same-day no-hot-water repair &mdash; $200&ndash;$500</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

